{
  "When interpreting a statistic, providing context means:": "",
  "Explaining what the number means in real-world terms, including units, population, and circumstances": "",
  "Rounding to the nearest whole number to simplify the presentation of the result": "",
  "Stating only the numerical value without providing any additional context or units": "",
  "Converting to a different unit of measurement so the audience can understand better": "",
  "Context connects the statistic to its real-world meaning—who was measured, what was measured, where, when, and why.": "",
  "A study reports that the mean commute time for workers in a city is 35 minutes. Without additional context, we cannot determine:": "",
  "That the mean is 35 and no additional context is needed to understand the result": "",
  "The unit of measurement used to collect the data for the commute time variable": "",
  "The average commute time without any additional details about the population studied": "",
  "Whether 35 minutes is considered long or short for that area, the sample size, or how varied commute times are": "",
  "A mean alone tells you the average but not the variability, sample size, comparison benchmarks, or whether the result is noteworthy.": "",
  "If a report says 'Sales increased by 50%,' what important context is missing?": "",
  "The standard deviation of the population from which the percentage was calculated": "",
  "Nothing; 50% is always impressive regardless of the baseline or total amount involved": "",
  "The baseline: 50% of $100 is $50, while 50% of $10 million is $5 million": "",
  "The z-score associated with the 50% mark in a standard normal distribution table": "",
  "A percentage change is meaningless without knowing the base amount. A 50% increase from a tiny base is very different from a 50% increase from a large base.": "",
  "A drug trial reports a 'statistically significant' reduction in blood pressure. What else should a reader consider?": "",
  "Whether the reduction is also clinically significant (large enough to matter for patient health)": "",
  "Nothing; statistical significance means the drug works and should be used immediately": "",
  "The color of the pill, which can influence how patients perceive the drug's effects": "",
  "Only the p-value, since it is the only measure that matters for evaluating a treatment": "",
  "Statistical significance means the result is unlikely due to chance, but the effect size may be too small to matter clinically. Context matters.": "",
  "Comparing the mean income of two countries without adjusting for cost of living is problematic because:": "",
  "Only medians should be used for income": "",
  "Income cannot be compared across countries": "",
  "A higher mean income in one country may buy less than a lower income in a country with cheaper costs": "",
  "Cost of living never affects statistical analysis": "",
  "Without adjusting for purchasing power, raw income figures can be misleading. Context (cost of living) is essential for valid comparisons.": "",
  "When a news headline says 'Study shows coffee drinkers live longer,' the key contextual question is:": "",
  "Whether the study shows correlation or causation, and what confounding variables might explain the association": "",
  "The sample size only, which determines the statistical power of the research study": "",
  "What brand of coffee was used in the study, as different brands may have different effects": "",
  "How much coffee they drank per day, since consumption levels affect the amount of caffeine": "",
  "Observational studies can show association but not causation. Coffee drinkers may differ from non-drinkers in many ways (exercise, diet), creating confounding variables.": "",
  "An outlier in a data set should be:": "",
  "Always removed immediately from the data set before any statistical analysis is performed": "",
  "Ignored entirely because outliers are always the result of errors in data collection": "",
  "Investigated to determine if it is a data error, a natural extreme, or a meaningful observation": "",
  "Replaced with the mean of the data set so that the overall distribution is not affected": "",
  "Context determines how to handle outliers. Some are data entry errors to be corrected; others are genuine extreme values that provide important information.": "",
  "The unemployment rate dropping from 5.0% to 4.8% might be reported as 'unemployment plunges.' This is potentially misleading because:": "",
  "0.2 percentage points is a very small change that may be within the margin of error": "",
  "All unemployment changes are significant": "",
  "The word 'plunges' is grammatically incorrect": "",
  "Unemployment rates should never be reported": "",
  "A 0.2 percentage point drop is modest and may not be statistically significant. Sensational language distorts the context of the change.": "",
  "Which factor is most important when determining if a survey result is meaningful?": "",
  "The font size of the report": "",
  "Whether the result matches expectations": "",
  "The sample size, sampling method, and margin of error": "",
  "The number of pages in the report": "",
  "A survey's reliability depends on how many people were sampled, how they were selected, and the margin of error—all critical context.": "",
  "When reporting the mean of a data set, it is best practice to also report:": "",
  "The mode only": "",
  "Only the mean is needed": "",
  "The data collector's name": "",
  "A measure of spread (such as SD or IQR) and the sample size": "",
  "A mean without a measure of spread or sample size leaves the reader unable to judge the precision or reliability of the estimate.": "",
  "What does 'interpreting data in context' mean?": "",
  "Performing more calculations on the data to generate additional numerical summaries": "",
  "Converting data into a graph so that the audience can visualize the distribution shape": "",
  "Memorizing the formulas used to compute the various statistics from the data set": "",
  "Explaining what statistical results mean in terms of the real-world situation from which the data came": "",
  "Interpreting in context means connecting numbers back to their real-world meaning—who, what, where, when, and why.": "",
  "What does 'confounding variable' mean?": "",
  "A variable that is measured correctly and has no error in its data collection process": "",
  "A variable that never changes and remains constant throughout the entire study period": "",
  "An unmeasured or uncontrolled variable that influences both the explanatory and response variables, distorting the apparent relationship": "",
  "The dependent variable in an experiment that is measured to assess the treatment effect": "",
  "A confounding variable creates a spurious association between two other variables because it affects both, making it look like one causes the other.": "",
  "What does 'practical significance' mean?": "",
  "A result that is easy to calculate using basic arithmetic operations without complexity": "",
  "A result that is published in a journal, which means it has been peer-reviewed formally": "",
  "Whether a result is large enough to be meaningful or useful in the real world, regardless of statistical significance": "",
  "The same as statistical significance, meaning both terms describe the same exact concept": "",
  "Practical significance asks: 'Is this result big enough to matter?' A tiny but statistically significant effect may have no practical importance.": "",
  "What does 'correlation does not imply causation' mean?": "",
  "Two variables moving together does not prove one causes the other; there may be confounders or the association may be coincidental": "",
  "Correlation is always meaningless and should never be reported in any research findings": "",
  "Correlation and causation are the same thing, so observing one implies the other exists": "",
  "Causation can be proven by any study design, including observational and survey methods": "",
  "Just because two variables are associated statistically does not mean one causes the other. Controlled experiments are needed to establish causation.": "",
  "What does 'margin of error' mean?": "",
  "The maximum value in the data set": "",
  "The difference between the mean and median": "",
  "The number of mistakes in data collection": "",
  "The range within which the true population parameter is likely to fall, based on sampling variability": "",
  "The margin of error quantifies the uncertainty in a sample estimate, typically expressed as ± some value (e.g., ±3%).": "",
  "What does 'effect size' mean?": "",
  "A measure of the magnitude of a difference or relationship, independent of sample size": "",
  "The number of variables measured in the study, which determines its overall complexity": "",
  "The p-value of a test, which indicates the probability of observing the data by chance": "",
  "The size of the data set, meaning how many total observations were collected overall": "",
  "Effect size tells you HOW BIG a difference or relationship is, complementing significance tests that only tell you whether the effect is nonzero.": "",
  "What is 'ecological fallacy'?": "",
  "A logical error that occurs when conclusions about individuals are drawn from group-level (aggregate) data": "",
  "An error in environmental science that occurs when ecosystems are improperly measured": "",
  "A mistake in calculating the mean by using incorrect values or dividing by a wrong count": "",
  "Using the wrong type of graph to display data, resulting in a misleading visualization": "",
  "The ecological fallacy assumes that relationships observed for groups also hold for individuals, which is often false.": "",
  "What does 'Simpson's Paradox' describe?": "",
  "A type of sampling bias": "",
  "A cartoon character's statistical adventures": "",
  "A method for calculating percentiles": "",
  "A phenomenon where a trend that appears in several groups reverses when the groups are combined": "",
  "Simpson's Paradox occurs when aggregated data show the opposite trend from the data in each subgroup, often caused by a lurking variable.": "",
  "What does 'generalizability' mean in statistics?": "",
  "Combining all data into one number": "",
  "The extent to which findings from a sample can be applied to the broader population": "",
  "Using only descriptive statistics": "",
  "Making general statements without data": "",
  "Generalizability depends on how well the sample represents the population. A biased or too-small sample limits generalizability.": "",
  "What does 'lurking variable' mean?": "",
  "The dependent variable": "",
  "A variable that is always visible in the data": "",
  "A variable that is measured but not reported": "",
  "A variable not included in the analysis that may affect the relationship between the variables being studied": "",
  "A lurking variable is hidden from the analysis and can create misleading associations between the variables being studied.": "",
  "A city reports that the average household income rose from $55,000 to $62,000 over five years. A politician claims residents are 'much better off.' What contextual information could challenge this claim?": "",
  "Only the tax rate matters when evaluating the significance of a salary increase": "",
  "Inflation rate, cost of living changes, whether the increase was driven by a few high earners, and whether the median also rose": "",
  "The population size of the city, which determines how many workers are affected overall": "",
  "Nothing; a $7,000 increase is always significant regardless of the broader economic context": "",
  "If inflation was 15% over those five years, the real increase is negative. If only a few wealthy newcomers raised the mean while the median stayed flat, typical residents are not better off.": "",
  "A hospital compares surgery success rates. Hospital A: 900/1000 (90%). Hospital B: 800/1000 (80%). Hospital A claims superiority. However, Hospital A mostly handles low-risk cases while Hospital B handles high-risk patients. What is this an example of?": "",
  "Measurement error that occurred during the data collection process at both hospitals": "",
  "A truncated y-axis issue that makes the mortality rate differences appear exaggerated": "",
  "Random sampling error that could be eliminated with a slightly larger patient sample": "",
  "Simpson's Paradox: when broken down by risk level, Hospital B may actually have higher success rates in each category": "",
  "Simpson's Paradox can make an aggregate comparison misleading. Stratifying by patient risk level (context) reveals the true picture.": "",
  "A study finds that ice cream sales and drowning deaths are positively correlated. A journalist writes 'Ice cream causes drowning.' What is wrong with this interpretation?": "",
  "Ice cream data should never be collected because it is not a serious research variable": "",
  "A lurking variable (hot weather) increases both ice cream sales and swimming activity, explaining the correlation without causation": "",
  "Correlation always implies causation, so ice cream truly does cause drowning incidents": "",
  "The study should have used a pie chart to display the relationship between the variables": "",
  "This is a classic example of confounding. Hot summer weather is the lurking variable that drives both ice cream consumption and swimming (hence drowning risk).": "",
  "A poll reports that 62% of voters support a new policy, with a margin of error of ±4%. What is the correct interpretation?": "",
  "We are confident the true level of support is between 58% and 66%": "",
  "62% minus 4% means only 58% support the policy": "",
  "Exactly 62% of the population supports the policy": "",
  "The poll is wrong because of the margin of error": "",
  "The margin of error creates a confidence interval (58% to 66%). The true population proportion likely falls within this range.": "",
  "A school district compares average test scores between a large urban school (n=2000, mean=72) and a small rural school (n=50, mean=78). An administrator concludes the rural school is definitively better. Why might this conclusion be premature?": "",
  "The 6-point difference is impossibly large and cannot be explained by any real variation": "",
  "Larger samples are always worse because they include too many outliers in the data": "",
  "The small rural school's mean is less reliable (higher margin of error), and demographic differences may confound the comparison": "",
  "Test scores cannot be compared between schools of different sizes under any circumstances": "",
  "With n=50, the rural school's mean has a wider margin of error. Also, differences in student demographics, funding, and resources are confounding factors.": "",
  "A company advertises that its product is 'recommended by 9 out of 10 dentists.' What contextual questions should a consumer ask?": "",
  "How were the dentists selected? How many were surveyed? What was the exact question asked? Were they paid?": "",
  "Only the brand name matters": "",
  "No questions needed; 90% approval is compelling": "",
  "Whether the dentists used the product themselves": "",
  "Without knowing the sampling method, sample size, question wording, and potential conflicts of interest, the '9 out of 10' claim lacks verifiable context.": "",
  "A charity reports it spent '95% of donations on programs.' Upon closer inspection, it paid a for-profit company owned by its CEO to 'run programs,' and that company kept 60% as profit. What data interpretation principle is violated?": "",
  "The range principle, which requires reporting the full spread of values in any claim": "",
  "Transparency and honest context: the statistic is technically true but practically misleading because it hides self-dealing": "",
  "The standard deviation rule, which limits how statistics may be communicated publicly": "",
  "The Empirical Rule, which describes the percentage of data within standard deviations": "",
  "A statistic can be technically accurate yet deeply misleading when crucial context (in this case, the financial arrangement) is hidden.": "",
  "A graph shows that Country A has twice the incarceration rate of Country B. Before concluding Country A is more dangerous, what contextual factors should be considered?": "",
  "No additional factors; higher incarceration means more crime and the data speak for themselves": "",
  "Only population size, which should be used to normalize the comparison between countries": "",
  "The graph's color scheme, which can influence the viewer's emotional response to the data": "",
  "Differences in sentencing laws, drug policy, reporting practices, and definitions of crime between the two countries": "",
  "Incarceration rates reflect not only crime rates but also sentencing severity, enforcement priorities, and legal frameworks—all essential context.": "",
  "A weight-loss supplement claims 'average weight loss of 15 pounds in 8 weeks.' The study had 10 participants, 3 dropped out, and the remaining 7 had losses ranging from 2 to 40 pounds. What contextual issues exist?": "",
  "The 3 dropouts should count as having lost 0 pounds": "",
  "Only the mean matters in advertising": "",
  "No issues; 15 pounds average is accurate for the 7 who completed the study": "",
  "Tiny sample size (7), high attrition (30%), large variability (2 to 40 lbs), no control group, and the mean is likely pulled up by the 40-lb outlier": "",
  "The claim is misleading due to the tiny sample, high dropout rate, no control group, wide variability, and an outlier inflating the mean.": "",
  "A state education department reports that 'graduation rates improved from 80% to 85%.' However, the definition of 'graduation' was changed during this period to include GED completers. What is the key interpretive issue?": "",
  "The improvement is real because 85% is greater than 80% and the numbers speak for themselves": "",
  "Changing the definition mid-measurement makes the comparison invalid; the increase may reflect a broader definition rather than actual improvement": "",
  "The old definition was wrong and should have always included GED completers from the start": "",
  "GED completers should always be included because they have earned equivalent qualifications": "",
  "When the definition of what is being measured changes, before-and-after comparisons become meaningless without adjusting for the definitional change.": ""
}